[
    {
        "content": "<p>In order to define a formal topology on an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> inside of a Heyting pretopos <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">E</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{E}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08944em;\">E</span></span></span></span> (i.e. using the internal logic), does the Heyting pretopos have to be an elementary topos?</p>",
        "id": 418692659,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706551645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think so. Isn't the whole point of formal topology to be predicative, by working with bases without completing them to locales?</p>",
        "id": 418707635,
        "sender_full_name": "Jonas Frey",
        "timestamp": 1706557415
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, which definition of formal topology are you using?</p>",
        "id": 418707743,
        "sender_full_name": "Jonas Frey",
        "timestamp": 1706557446
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You might need a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span></span></span></span>-pretopos or a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>-pretopos though, depending on the definition and how internal you want it to be.</p>",
        "id": 418710339,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1706558464
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a relevant paper by Van den Berg and Moerdijk at <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/0912.1242.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/0912.1242.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 418713585,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706559710
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is the cover relation that is the potentially impredicative part of the formal topology, since it is a relation between elements of a formal topology and subsets of the formal topology, so it is unclear how one would internalize such a relation in a Heyting pretopos without power sets. </p>\n<p>However, it seems that Ayberk Tosun in his article on formal topology <a href=\"https://odr.chalmers.se/server/api/core/bitstreams/84989823-7398-4eb3-8804-1f88822d1fd2/content\">https://odr.chalmers.se/server/api/core/bitstreams/84989823-7398-4eb3-8804-1f88822d1fd2/content</a> provides a definition of a formal topology which does not require the cover relation to be defined, and thus it is predicative. Since Tosun is working in dependent type theory, this implies that formal topologies are definable in any <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>-pretopos. The cover relation on the formal topology is inductively defined, but it still uses power sets in the article, so that part is still impredicative.</p>",
        "id": 418737457,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706569745
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In type theory you can go a long way if you're careful about universe level. E.g. power set is okay predicatively as long as you recognise it belongs to the next universe level up. That might be what Tosun is doing.</p>",
        "id": 418798061,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706607243
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you want to do that kind of argument in the internal language of a locally cartesian closed category directly, you need the extra assumption that your category has enough universes. That's usually a safe assumption,  in the sense that it holds in most natural examples of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>-pretoposes, although a little inelegant, since universes aren't uniquely defined up to isomorphism by universal properties.</p>",
        "id": 418798094,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706607247
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But absent any universes, such as a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Π</mi><mi>W</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Pi W</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Π</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">W</span></span></span></span>-pretopos with internal fullness but nothing else, this argument doesn't go through.</p>",
        "id": 418813751,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706612985
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also, with enough universes, you might as well just use frames and locales directly (usually considered impredicative) and just recognize that the frames and locales lie in the next universe level.</p>",
        "id": 418815777,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706613791
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's hard to say whether universes are necessary without looking at the details of the proofs. If there's a proof in type theory that uses universes then sometimes it's very easy to remove them and make the argument work in an arbirtary lcc, sometimes it's possible but non trivial, like the derivation of dependent W-types from non-dependent W-types, and sometimes it's impossible, like the proof coproducts are disjoint. For proofs involving formal topologies I think it's worth checking to make sure they can be made to work without universes.</p>",
        "id": 418816115,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706613911
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If fullness is referring to the fullness/subset collection axiom, then it's not clear how to even state it internally without either a universe or a class of small maps, like in algebraic set theory.<br>\nEdit: I suppose you can use stack semantics to state fullness, so that would avoid using universes.</p>",
        "id": 418816124,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706613915
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"671813\">Madeleine Birchfield</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Internal.20formal.20topologies.20in.20a.20Heyting.20pretopos/near/418815777\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Also, with enough universes, you might as well just use frames and locales directly (usually considered impredicative) and just recognize that the frames and locales lie in the next universe level.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's possible, but formal topologies can still be useful. In the paper by Gambino at <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1016/j.apal.2005.05.021\">https://doi.org/10.1016/j.apal.2005.05.021</a> the truth values in a Heyting valued model of set theory are elements of a frame, which can be a proper class, but to prove soundness it's important that the frame comes from a set presented formal topology.</p>",
        "id": 418817233,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706614371
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What happens if you replace the set of truth values <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> with a dominance <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Σ</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Sigma \\subseteq \\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Σ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> in the definition of cover or formal topology?</p>",
        "id": 418819465,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706615289
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276787\">Andrew Swan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Internal.20formal.20topologies.20in.20a.20Heyting.20pretopos/near/418816124\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If fullness is referring to the fullness/subset collection axiom, then it's not clear how to even state it internally without either a universe or a class of small maps, like in algebraic set theory.<br>\nEdit: I suppose you can use stack semantics to state fullness, so that would avoid using universes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Speaking of the stack semantics, a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P:A \\to \\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> into the set of truth values is equivalently a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> with an injection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>; internally in a category this is an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> with a monomorphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. So I wonder if we could use the stack semantics to define the inductive covers without using universes.</p>",
        "id": 418821495,
        "sender_full_name": "Madeleine Birchfield",
        "timestamp": 1706616089
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"671813\">Madeleine Birchfield</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Internal.20formal.20topologies.20in.20a.20Heyting.20pretopos/near/418819465\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>What happens if you replace the set of truth values <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> with a dominance <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Σ</mi><mo>⊆</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Sigma \\subseteq \\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Σ</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> in the definition of cover or formal topology?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I guess that makes sense as a definition, but the question is how it would work with examples. E.g. the Heyting algebra of open sets of real numbers is a proper class in a predicative setting - you can deal with this by working with a set presentation of formal topology, but it's still useful to have some way of talking about arbitary open sets.</p>",
        "id": 418821832,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706616224
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"671813\">Madeleine Birchfield</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Internal.20formal.20topologies.20in.20a.20Heyting.20pretopos/near/418821495\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276787\">Andrew Swan</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Internal.20formal.20topologies.20in.20a.20Heyting.20pretopos/near/418816124\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If fullness is referring to the fullness/subset collection axiom, then it's not clear how to even state it internally without either a universe or a class of small maps, like in algebraic set theory.<br>\nEdit: I suppose you can use stack semantics to state fullness, so that would avoid using universes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Speaking of the stack semantics, a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P:A \\to \\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span> into the set of truth values is equivalently a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> with an injection <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>; internally in a category this is an object <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> with a monomorphism <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\to A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>. So I wonder if we could use the stack semantics to define the inductive covers without using universes.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Yes, that might work.</p>",
        "id": 418822088,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Swan",
        "timestamp": 1706616314
    }
]